Every little girl has once dreamed of being a figure skater; however, few actually know the price kids have to pay to reach their Olympic dreams. Historically, figure skating has been one of the most aesthetically demanding sports in the world: athletic power is wrapped in the expectation of effortless grace. For decades, that expectation came with a mental health cost, particularly for the young athletes. The 2026 Milan Cortina Winter Olympics, however, offered something different: an example of how important mental health is in elite skating and how learning to manage the pressure at this level can lead to success. Alysa Liu and Ilia Malinin are helping redefine what mental health in elite skating can look like through their presence on and off the ice.

Mental health is not a side issue in sports; it is the center of performance. When athletes lose control over their own bodies, choices, and identities just to win medals, they break. Figure skating doesn't need to be convinced that mental health matters anymore. The question for figure skating now is whether it can change fast enough to protect the next generation.

## The Cult of Flawless Perfection

Leading up to Beijing 2022, women's figure skating was dominated by a rotating cast of very young Russian girls trained under coach Eteri Tutberidze, known to lead a very harsh training program, with repetitive practices and strict monitoring of the athletes' weight, which affected the physical and mental health of these young girls. In sports where aesthetics and perfection are the main attraction points, athletes often develop eating disorders and other harmful practices, being encouraged by authority figures such as coaches.

Most often, failure to perform flawlessly at a high competitive level is associated with depression or other mental health struggles. An article in the *Psychiatry Times* discusses the case of Kamilla Valieva at the 2022 Beijing Olympics. At the Beijing 2022 Olympics, Valieva missed the podium after her free skate performance was filled with mistakes. She was reprimanded by her coach, Tutberidze, for it, which made the audience feel the "chillness." Following her performance and a positive doping test, the International Skating Union highlighted deep issues within the system and voted to raise the minimum competition age to 17, starting with the 2024–25 season. This was seen as a protective measure for the physical and mental health of young athletes.

## The New Generation of Figure Skaters

Alysa Liu's story is perhaps one of the most powerful examples of the effect of mental health on high-performance sports. Liu became the youngest-ever U.S. Figure Skating champion in 2019 at age 13, then retired at 16 after competing at the Beijing Olympics. Her father stated that she "would no longer go anywhere near the rink" as she suffered from PTSD.

This year, she detailed her decision to retire: she was overtrained as a child, had no days off, and no control over what she ate or drank. Alysa decided to return to her sport in 2024, but this time on her own terms: she chooses her own program music, contributes to the creative process, adjusts her training load based on how she feels, and is no longer subject to dietary control. She prioritizes herself and her mental health. The result was extraordinary. She won the 2025 World Championships and then took double gold at the 2026 Olympics. She came back to focus on how she can help reshape the sport to make it safer for young athletes.

In contrast to Liu's story, Ilia Malinin chose to tell his story with the pressure of figure skating in real time. The 21-year-old American skater, known as the "Quad God," was undefeated for over 2 years and arrived in Milan-Cortina as the favorite for the individual gold medal. After topping the short program, he fell twice in the free skate and finished eighth. He immediately spoke of being "overwhelmed" by the "unreal" pressure of being the gold-medal favorite at the Olympics.

What made his response significant to the need for change in this sport was what came next. In an Instagram post, Malinin wrote: "On the world's biggest stage, those who appear the strongest may still be fighting invisible battles on the inside. Even your happiest memories can end up tainted by the noise. Vile online hatred attacks the mind, and fear lures it into the darkness, no matter how hard you try to stay sane through the endless insurmountable pressure. It all builds up as these moments flash before your eyes, resulting in an inevitable crash."

Rather than disappearing, Malinin used the Olympic figure skating gala to make a statement on the importance of mental health. Wearing a gray hoodie with "Fear" written upside down, he performed a routine that symbolically confronted the negative impact of social media, ending it with his famous backflip.

Former champion Gracie Gold, who has been open about her own mental health struggles, described the isolating nature of the experience. She calls it the "aquarium effect": you're in the tank, everyone is staring, and when things start to go wrong, it is not an environment conducive to calmness.

The 2025 World Figure Skating Championships in Boston marked the start of the "Calm Zones," dedicated safe spaces for athletes to relax at major skating competitions. The International Skating Union has also approved a social media monitoring program to protect athletes from online harassment and has placed mental health at the center of its Vision 2030 strategic plan. The U.S. Figure Skating Association has employed a full-time head of sport psychology since the 1970s, who now attends development camps and junior competitions specifically to build relationships with skaters before they reach the senior level.

With this shift in generations, we can see a shift in mentality. Alysa Liu and Ilia Malinin are just the latest examples of how much impact they can have on changing their sport for the better. Their journeys were not easy, but they showed their strength by being vulnerable, which made them the faces of mental health advocacy within figure skating and the whole sports community.
